<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What does Aida 14 mean?", answer: "Aida 14 means the fabric has 14 holes, and therefore 14 stitches, per inch. Higher counts have more, smaller holes per inch, which produces finer detail and a smaller finished design. Aida 11 is very coarse and beginner friendly, Aida 14 is the most common choice, Aida 16 and 18 are finer, and Aida 22 (also called Hardanger) is quite fine. The same stitch pattern will look smaller on a higher-count fabric." },
  { question: "How much margin should I add to cross-stitch fabric?", answer: "Three inches of margin on every side (six inches total in each direction) is the standard recommendation for most projects. This leaves room for the hoop or scroll frame to clamp onto blank fabric, keeps your stitching away from the frayed edges, and provides enough fabric for framing in a mat later. For very small designs, two inches may be enough. For large projects that will be stretched over foam board or professionally framed, add four inches per side." },
  { question: "What's the difference between Aida and evenweave?", answer: "Aida is a cotton fabric woven with distinct blocks that create obvious holes at the corners, making it easy to see where each cross stitch goes. Evenweave fabrics like Lugana, Jobelan, and linen have smooth, plain-woven construction where the threads are evenly spaced but there are no visible holes. Aida is recommended for beginners and designs with whole stitches. Evenweave is preferred for designs with fractional stitches, backstitch detail, and a more refined finished look." },
  { question: "Why do I stitch over 2 threads on linen?", answer: "Linen and fine evenweaves have threads that are too small to stitch over individually, so the convention is to stitch over 2 threads per stitch. This effectively halves the count: 28-count linen stitched over 2 gives the same stitch density as 14-count Aida. Stitching over 2 also looks cleaner because each cross straddles a thread intersection, which hides any slight imperfection in the weave and gives a smoother finished surface." },
  { question: "How do I calculate fabric size from stitch count?", answer: "Divide the stitch count in each direction by the effective stitches per inch (fabric count divided by stitches-over), then add twice your margin. For example, a 140 by 140 stitch design on Aida 14 is 140 / 14 = 10 inches in each direction. Adding 3 inches of margin on each side gives 16 by 16 inches of fabric to buy. This calculator handles all the math automatically and shows the size in both inches and centimeters." }
]) %>

